, and migration. He then summarizes the factors which limit the geographic extent of gene flow, and those which allow steep clines to develop in the absence of barriers to gene flow. His analysis draws on examples from the field, experiments, and single- and multiple-locus models. The mechanism and conditions for parapatric speciation are presented: steepening clines, development into hybrid zones, and the evolution of sexual isolation. In the final chapter the author considers the interpretation of natural clines and the associated geographic patterns of subspecies and species.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aClines. 0aEvolution (Biology). 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aAllo-parapatric.  aAllopatry.  aCline.  aCoadaptation.  aCompetition.  aContact, primary.  aDeme.  aDensity effects.  aDifferentiation, measurement of.  aDisjunction.  aEmergence time.  aGene flow.  aHeterozygous advantage.  aHybrid zone.  aIntergradation, primary.  aMating, assortative.  aNull point.  aOverlap.  aParapatry.  aRassenkreis.  aShifting effects.  aSpeciation.  aSympatry.  aallopatrie.  ab, slope of selection gradient.  aeffects.  amodification.  asecondary.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209456.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK